            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Koval\u2019s story is a testament to grit, a narrative written in the steep streets of San Francisco. Raised in Modesto, she was the daughter of a mechanic and a grocery store cashier who valued a hard day's work over a college degree. For them, life was about providing, not aspiring. Heather, however, felt a pull toward the coastal fog and the promise of a different life. Graduating high school with decent grades but no funds for further education, she packed a single suitcase and moved to San Francisco at 19, crashing on a friend\u2019s couch in the Outer Richmond.\n\nHer entry into the world of finance was through the service door. She landed a job as a receptionist at a small mortgage brokerage in the Financial District. While her peers were in lecture halls, Heather was learning the industry from the ground up, observing the intricate dance of numbers, risk, and human desire. She was sharp, organized, and possessed an uncanny ability to calm anxious first-time homebuyers. A senior partner, recognizing her raw talent and ambition, mentored her, encouraging her to get her mortgage loan originator license.\n\nThe 2008 financial crisis was her trial by fire. While others fled the industry, Heather dug in, building a reputation for integrity and resilience. She climbed the ranks steadily, her lack of a degree compensated for by two decades of hard-won experience.\n\nNow 43, Heather lives a life she once only dreamed of. She resides in a chic, modern apartment in North Beach, a 1.2-mile walk from her office. Her daily routine is a ritual: a morning espresso from a local cafe, the brisk walk down Columbus Avenue, and long days demystifying jumbo loans for tech executives. Socially, she has a tight-knit circle of friends, a chosen family forged over years of city living. Romantically, she\u2019s had partners, but her career has often been her primary focus.\n\nHaving achieved financial security, Heather\u2019s aspirations are shifting. She dreams of traveling extensively and perhaps buying a small, quiet cottage in Mendocino County as a weekend escape. She\u2019s a true San Franciscan now\u2014shaped by its demands, thriving on its energy, and finally secure enough to imagine a life beyond the hustle."
        },
